<table cellspacing="20px">
<tr>
<th align="left"><h1>Aravind Joshi Honored by the NLP Community and Penn Engineering</h1>
</th>
</tr>


<tr>
<td><a href="https://www.cis.upenn.edu/joshi-fest/index.html"><img src="../assets/images/joshifest.jpg" width="533" height="355" alt="PHOTO: JoshiFest" /></a>
<div class="views-field-field-photo-data">
 <p class="field-content" align="left">Eduardo Glandt and Aravind Joshi</p></div></td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<div id="mainContent.two-column" class="clearfix" >



  <p>The Natural Language Processing (NLP) and Penn Engineering communities celebrated Aravind Joshi,  Henry  Salvatori Professor of Computer and Cognitive Science, for his many years of achievements and contributions, <a href="https://www.cis.upenn.edu/joshi-fest/index.html">at a symposium in his honor</a> at the University  of Pennsylvania on October 22, 2012. </p>
  <p><br />
    For researchers in Natural Language Processing (NLP), it is difficult to  imagine research in the field without the presence of Aravind Joshi. In every aspect  of the field to which he has turned his attention, Joshi has changed the way  scholars think about its central concerns. At the symposium, several of these scholars were given the chance to highlight Joshi’s insights and influence, and  convey their personal thanks. </p>
  <p><br />
    Several, including <strong>Barbara Grosz </strong>(Harvard University), <strong>Scott Weinstein </strong>(University of Pennsylvania)<strong> </strong>and<strong> Lyn Walker </strong>(UC Santa Cruz)<strong> </strong>focused on Joshi’s contributions to discourse, dialogue and pragmatics. Working with <strong>Grosz</strong> and <strong>Weinstein</strong>, Joshi introduced a theory of prominence in discourse meant to account for ease of inference and the use of anaphoric expressions, linked by the observation that an entity that can be accessed with an expression as small as a pronoun must also be prominent. The theory combines local and grammatical information (e.g. whether potential pronoun antecedents are subjects or objects) with a more global stack discipline reflecting the hierarchy of informational tasks in discourse. With Joshi and Ellen Prince as her advisors, <strong>Lyn Walker</strong> showed how the theory applies in practice to naturally occurring dialogues.</p>
  <p><br />
    Other researchers focused on Joshi’s fundamental contributions in formal syntax. Joshi’s work here was a response to Chomsky's challenge to mathematical linguistics to characterize the grammatical mechanisms available to human languages. What is the weakest class of grammars, or equivalently, automata, that generate natural languages? Joshi's contribution to this central question  was the development of Tree-Adjoining Grammars (TAGs), the only popular mathematical model of language in which the primitives are trees rather than strings. As <strong>Bob Frank</strong> (Yale University) put it in his presentation, TAGs are “as simple as possible, but not simpler”. Or as <strong>Mark Steedman</strong> (University of Edinburgh) put it, one should fight to “keep TAG lean and mean”, that many claim   more power than basic TAG is needed for human language should be tested to  destruction as a threat to the enterprise.</p>
  <p><br />
    In addition to being subjected to meta-theoretical  analysis, TAG has been applied to natural language parsing, and generation, noted  in the presentation by <strong>Kevin Knight</strong> (ISI), semantic interpretation, and language curriculum, noted  in the presentation by <strong>Srinivas  Bangalore</strong> (ATT Research). The influence of TAG on linguistics, as well as on  himself as a linguist, was highlighted in the presentation given by <strong>Tony Kroch</strong> (University of  Pennsylvania}.</p>
  <p><br />
    All of the  speakers who had spent time at Penn, especially those who had done so as  graduate students – <strong>Rajeev Sangal</strong> (IIIT Hyderabad), <strong>Kathy McKeown</strong> (Columbia University), <strong>Julia Hirschberg</strong> (Columbia University), <strong>Srinivas  Bangalore</strong> (ATT Research), <strong>Jerry  Kaplan</strong>, <strong>Lyn Walker</strong>, <strong>Rao  Kosaraju</strong>, <strong>Kathleen McCo</strong>y, <strong>Yves Schabes</strong>, <strong>Fei Xia</strong> – stressed the incredible sense of community  Joshi had  built up within the School of Computer &amp; Information Science, which he had co-founded  with Saul Gorn in 1972. They also have positive  memories of the founding of Penn’s Institute for Research in Cognitive Science (IRCS) in 1978. Funding for IRCS first came from the Sloan Foundation, and  later in 1991 from the National Science Foundation, as a multidisciplinary  research partnership of investigators from the disciplines of Computer Science,  Linguistics, Mathematical Logic, Philosophy and Neuroscience. It nurtured  researchers from all these disciplines, and was illustrated at the symposium in the talks from <strong>Tony Kroch</strong> (Linguistics,  University of Pennsylvania), <strong>Charles Yang</strong> (Psychology, University of Pennsylvania) and <strong>Scott Weinstein</strong> (Philosophy, University of Pennsylvania).</p>
  <p><br />
    Article excerpted in part from “<a href="http://www.let.rug.nl/nerbonne/misc/joshi-laudatio.html">A  Brief Laudatio</a>,” John Nerbonne, ACL Lifetime Achievement Award presentation,  2002.   </p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
			    <p>
